50|$|In 2002, Bluestone {{established}} residential lending {{operations in}} New Zealand, and in 2004, the business started {{work on a}} <b>reverse</b> <b>mortgage</b> unit, specialising in lending to retirees, {{many of whom are}} 'asset-rich, cash-poor'. Bluestone was the first major non-bank <b>reverse</b> <b>mortgage</b> lender in Australia, and the first lender in Australia to offer a 'fixed for life' product so that borrowers were not exposed to long dated interest rate risk. Bluestone's lump sum <b>reverse</b> <b>mortgage</b> product was expanded to include a 'draw-down' style product in 2006, allowing borrowers to receive funds in regular payments. A 'capped for life' product soon followed, and in 2007, the <b>reverse</b> <b>mortgage</b> product was launched in New Zealand.|$|E
